Registered validators can do finetuning on the network itself. You can always finetune your own model and serve it to the network (that's the mining part)

The goal for the Validator is to get an AI model with the lowest loss.
The goal for the Miner is to have the biggest delta-loss on the validator.
So, the more you manage to lower the loss of the validator, the more profits you earn.
The validators in return score the miners, which then get used to calculate rewards (which get split 50/50)

```Registered validators can do finetuning on the network itself.```
So, when validators do funetuning, other miners(the computers from other people) join this training?
The validators do a teacher-student traing, or MoE.
Ping the network, get results, use that data to do a backpass on their own model, rinse and repeat.
The better the results, the lower the loss values, the more you finetune the model, the better the payout.

So you want to have a diverse set of models that lower the overall loss of the network. If you put too many models on the network, and the network is not diverse enough, the network will automatically diverge to those with the best delta loss and you won't be able to add more models on the network without incurring penalties.

I've been here for a little while and seen the Network grow, so I figured I'd just share some useful insights for the new people. To start, Bittensor is a project that requires a lot of time to understand fully. It's easy to be overwhelmed, and quite difficult if you've never worked with Linux/ML before. ChatGPT is a great tool to help you learn commands and how that side of things work - which is going to be essential if you're building things on the network, or have any desire to become a validator/miner in the future.

A lot of information can be found by searching the various channels in the Bittensor Network section.
